   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157574_1842_04_20_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1842-04-20">Thurs April 20<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>
                  1842.</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RobiJ1">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Robinson</persName>
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>Alas my poor little<lb/>
               weak body will not<lb/>
               allow me to follow<lb/>
               my mind's wishes. Tho'<lb/>
               I have much recovered<lb/>
               health and strength<lb/>
               here under <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriets</persName>
               <lb/>
               tender nursing and<lb/>
               my physicians skillful<lb/> 
               treatment yet I have been<lb/>
               warned within these<lb/>
               few days by symptoms<lb/>
               not to be neglected tho<lb/>
               not actually alarming <lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157574_1842_04_20_page02.jpg"/>
               that I must not venture<lb/>
               away from my physician <lb/>
               and that I am not yet<lb/>
               strong enough for all<lb/>
               the pleasure and all the<lb/>
               excitement I should<lb/>
               have in your society -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I must relinquish my<lb/>
               hope of going to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Armagh_IE">Armagh</placeName>
               <lb/>
               But I would not for any<lb/>
               consideration give up<lb/>
               my promise to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lucy</persName> to <lb/>
               carry her there unless<lb/>
               I had seen from your<lb/>
               dear <persName>Marys</persName> note that<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157574_1842_04_20_page03.jpg"/>
               she need not be deprived<lb/>
               of the great pleasure &amp;<lb/>
               advantage of her visit<lb/>
               by my weakness of health<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>My dear friend you <lb/>
               are in good plight<lb/>
               and can come and go<lb/>
               and do what you please<lb/>
               must make me amends<lb/>
               for my disappointment<lb/>
               whenever you can - And<lb/>
               I am sure you will.<lb/>
               You said something to me<lb/>
               very like a promise that<lb/>
               you would bring <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrewD1">Brewster</persName>
               <lb/>
               to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworthstown</placeName>  - But<lb/>
               you fixed no time &amp; so <lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157574_1842_04_20_page04.jpg"/>
               long as time is unfixed<lb/>
               a promised <add>visit</add> is good for<lb/>
               little - Be pleased to say,<lb/>
               (tell <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lucy</persName> if you have not<lb/>
               time to write),<lb/>
               When you expect <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BrewD1">Sir David</persName>
               <lb/>
               and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ExxxX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> E</persName> &amp; I will write<lb/>
               forthwith to engage him.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I have given <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lucy</persName> all<lb/>
               my loves to carry to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">Miss<lb/>
               Robinson</persName> lest they should<lb/>
               trouble you or you <choice>
                  <orig>shd</orig>
                  <reg>should</reg>
               </choice> forget<lb/>
               them - </p>
            <lb/>
            <p>I wish you would<lb/>
               tell <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lucy</persName> to tell me what is<lb/>
               amiss about the pendulum<lb/>
               as a measurer - I have been<lb/>
               put all through <hi rend="underline">other</hi> by the <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157574_1842_04_20_page05.jpg"/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <title ref="./Workography.xml#Janus1">Edinburgh Review</title> on weights<lb/>
               &amp; measures &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KateH1">Kater</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WollW1">Wollaston</persName>
            </p>
            <lb/>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#KateH1">Kater</persName> I don't care about but<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WollW1">Wollaston</persName> I do<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               Yours with sincere esteem<lb/>
               &amp; affectionately<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_157574_1842_04_20_page06.jpg"/>
            <postscript>
               <p>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RobiJ1">The Rev &amp; D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Robinson</persName>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <closer>
